    <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
      <subfield code="a">Three works bound together and copied in different hands. The first is a collection of moral anecdotes; the second is a short work on Islamic practice regarding women also known as Kuls̲ūm nanah (or Kuls̲ūmʹnanah); it contains an introduction, 15 chapters and a conclusion; the third is an unidentified leaf summarizing rules regarding men and women.</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield tag="505" ind1="0" ind2=" ">
      <subfield code="a">1. f. 1v-130v: Hāz̲ā kitāb Sirāj al-munīr -- 2. f. 133v-146v: ʻAqāyid al-nisā -- 3. f. 147r-147v: [unidentified leaf]</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
      <subfield code="a">Layout: First work written in 10 long lines; second work in 20 long lines; third work in 14 long lines.</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
      <subfield code="a">Script: Written in nastaʻlīq in black ink; pointed.</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
      <subfield code="a">Decoration: First page border-ruled in red; some rubrications in red.</subfield>
    </datafield>
    <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
      <subfield code="a">Origin: The second item is dated 1241 A.H. (f. 146v) the first item was likely copied at a similar time.</subfield>
